description.plain:
“Rushing Back” is a song by Australian electronic producer Flume, featuring fellow Australian singer Vera Blue.

Flume and Blue had previously collaborated on his cover of “My Boo” for Triple J’s Like a Version series. This song marks the first original collaboration between the two artists

The song was first premiered to the public at The Osheaga Music and Arts Festival on August 2nd, 2019, as a part of a brand new live show.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zlhwlTk6HAg

This song is about being sentimental – thinking about old experiences and feeling old emotions, and coming to terms with the fact that they have passed.

description.plain:
Written together with veteran producers Andy and Thom Mak and Melbourne songstress Gossling, “Hold” has resulted in a real, raw and powerful song.

Hold is the first song in her five-track album, it’s a song about finding someone who pulls you out of a dark place. It’s about when you’ve opened your heart so many times to people and you finally find that person who is there to protect you, to look after you, even when you’ve hurt them and they’ve hurt you. You never give up on them.

Vera once said in an interview, “I’ve always wanted to create something that’s a blend of folk and cool, heavy, thick sounds. This is the music I have been wanting to make and I feel like I’m unleashing.”

annotations:
I have opened my heart so many times
 You have a hold of it now
 I need you to breathe new life into me
 You have a hold of it now

After being in a vulnerable position, it seems easier to push others away, as a defense mechanism.
However, sometimes it is okay to open up your heart. Clearly, Vera was apprehensive to let this person into her life, but once she understood that he/she was willing to stick by her through her tough time, she let herself open up to them.
Obviously, a rebound relationship is not the healthiest, but neither is drowning in your insecurities. Vera took the time to self-reflect, but also consider the possibility of starting a new relationship with someone. Another person can only have a hold of your heart, if you allow them to.

All those times I tried to make you forget me
 You stayed, you stayed
 All those times I tried to make you forget me
 You stayed

This is such a relatable line. Sometimes, people push others away, especially if they know the other person has feelings for them. Whether it is a defense mechanism or a way of bluntly saying no, sometimes it is okay to open up your heart. Clearly, Vera was apprehensive to let this person into her life, but once she understood that he/she was willing to stick by her through her tough time, she let herself open up to them.

I can be young and reckless
 But you stayed

Sometimes, we all get spurred up by emotion, and lash out at those we love. Despite her tornado of emotions, especially after being in a dark place, her partner is willing to stay by her side, and help her sort through it. Her partner is making her stronger, rather than taking advantage of her insecurities and of her past.

I knew when you took me over
 That you where not like the others

Clearly, Vera, or the character of the song, has had her heart broken before. She was in a vulnerable place, but after her partner came around and showed that he/she was willing to stay, Vera realized that her partner is worth opening her heart for.

I tried to loosen off your hold
 But you stayed and nothing made you fall

Vera says that this song is about someone pulling her out of a hard place, and this line perfectly reflects that. Often, when we are extremely vulnerable or don’t want our feelings to get hurt again, we close ourselves off to others, especially to second (or more) chances. Whether it was a breakup or other issue, Vera’s partner stuck by her no matter how hard she tried to push the possibility of love away.

When I am yours
 When we are home

Vera saying that she feels loved and humbled by her partner, it creates a sense of peace. Home is supposed to be the place where you are comfortable and able to live freely, which is how she feels when she is with her partner. In the second line of the song, she sings, “false words would never be allowed” because her partner doesn’t want a false image of Vera; he/she wants the true Vera.

I love the way you tie me down
 False words would never be allowed

Vera’s partner humbles her by “bringing her back to Earth”. Sometimes, we start thinking that we are better than others, especially our partners, but her partner is good at tethering her. Through him/her, she realizes she doesn’t need to put on a show for anyone, and she can be herself. She doesn’t have to act falsely, or say false things about herself, since her partner is so accepting.

The first line is not necessarily “bad”; there is not a bad connotation here. Vera seems to love the way she feels when she is with her partner, and their partner humbles and completes her.

You loved the many faults you found
 You kept what was worth keeping around

Vera says that although she has many flaws, her partner loved each one. She goes on to further explain that she is worth keeping, and she’s glad that after many times of people letting her down and tossing her aside, someone has finally kept her.
